Here is the fix for the bug:

```diff
diff --git a/gson/src/main/java/com/google/gson/internal/bind/JsonAdapterAnnotationTypeAdapterFactory.java b/gson/src/main/java/com/google/gson/internal/bind/JsonAdapterAnnotationTypeAdapterFactory.java
index 30c4f6e9..b52e1573 100644
--- a/gson/src/main/java/com/google/gson/internal/bind/JsonAdapterAnnotationTypeAdapterFactory.java
+++ b/gson/src/main/java/com/google/gson/internal/bind/JsonAdapterAnnotationTypeAdapterFactory.java
@@ -64,7 +64,9 @@ public final class JsonAdapterAnnotationTypeAdapterFactory implements TypeAdapte
       throw new IllegalArgumentException(
           "@JsonAdapter value must be TypeAdapter or TypeAdapterFactory reference.");
     }
+    if (typeAdapter != null) {
       typeAdapter = typeAdapter.nullSafe();
+    }
     return typeAdapter;
   }
 }
```

## Summary of the fix

The issue was in the `getTypeAdapter` method of `JsonAdapterAnnotationTypeAdapterFactory`. The code was unconditionally calling `.nullSafe()` on the type adapter, even when the adapter was `null`. This caused a `NullPointerException` when a TypeAdapterFactory returned `null` (which is valid behavior for preventing recursion, as shown in the test case).

The fix adds a null check before calling `typeAdapter.nullSafe()`, ensuring that the null-safe wrapper is only applied when the type adapter is not null. This preserves the intended behavior while preventing the crash.

